            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sofia Volkov was born not in San Francisco, but in a city that no longer exists: Leningrad, 1975. Her childhood was defined by the waning years of the Soviet Union\u2014the quiet dignity of her librarian mother, who could make a cozy haven from a cramped apartment, and the stoic resilience of her factory-worker father. The scarcity of her youth taught her to cherish well-made objects and the warmth of a thoughtfully arranged space. When the family immigrated to San Francisco in the early 1990s, the chaotic vibrancy of the city was a shock, a world away from the grey conformity she knew.\n\nTo navigate this new world, Sofia enrolled at City College, earning a practical Associate's degree in Business Administration. It wasn\u2019t a passion, but a tool. For years, she worked in other people\u2019s retail stores, absorbing everything about inventory, customer service, and the relentless pace of commerce. The turning point came with her mother's passing. Going through her modest belongings, Sofia was struck again by her mother\u2019s talent for creating beauty out of very little. It was a quiet rebellion against bleakness.\n\nWith a small inheritance and her life\u2019s savings, Sofia took the ultimate risk. She leased a ground-floor retail space in Russian Hill with a small apartment above it, fulfilling the 0.0-mile commute dream. She poured her grief, her memories, and her business acumen into \"Hearth & Lume,\" her independent home goods store. The shop is a reflection of her past: minimalist, soulful, and filled with handcrafted ceramics, worn linen, and objects with a story.\n\nNow 49, Sofia\u2019s life is woven into the fabric of her neighborhood. Her days begin with arranging new pottery in the shop window and end with a glass of wine on her fire escape, watching the fog roll in. She\u2019s divorced, a brief and mismatched union from her late twenties, and has since found deeper companionship in her tight-knit circle of other local merchants and loyal customers. Sofia\u2019s dream is simple yet profound: to keep her small kingdom afloat against the tide of e-commerce and to continue offering a small piece of curated tranquility in the heart of the bustling city that finally feels like home."
